This is amongst the reasons why you should [favor composition over inheritance](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_over_inheritance). The way you design it, you _shouldn&#39;t_ mock the super call because it&#39;s part of the tested class&#39; behavior.

Rather than extending the existing user service, use it as a data source, then you can mock it.

As in

```
public class CustomerUserService implements SlpUserService {
  private final SlpUserService sourceService;
  public CustomerUserService(SlpUserService source) {
    sourceService = source; // rather than super(source)
  }

  @Override
  public User getUserForID(final String userId) {
    User user = sourceService.getUserForUID(userId);
    // work with user
  }
}
```

Then you can mock the `DefaultUserService` easily - in fact, you can pass in any `SlpUserService` implementation, making it more flexible..

You can of course always overengineer and also extract the &quot;work with user object&quot; part.

```
class UserProcessor implements SlpUserService {
  private final SlpUserService sourceService;
  private final Consumer&lt;User&gt; processor;

  // constructor tbd
  @Override
  public User getUserForID(final String userId) {
    User user = sourceService.getUserForUID(userId);
    processor.accept(user);
    return user;
  }
}
```

Then you only need to verify that 1. the passed in user service is used as a data source and 2. the user it provides is passed to the consumer for processing after returning it. This way, you can unit test the concrete user service and actual processing part separately.

