answers.body_markdown:
Answers for you.

First, you need to bind the fields before reading the bean. `Binder#readBean` as stated by documentation is populating the **bound** fields. Naturally the fields not yet bound, will not get populated.

    Person person = personService.getPerson(key);
    binder.bindInstanceFields(form);
    binder.readBean(person);

Also note, that in order to find the fields, the Binder#bindInstanceFields method requires the naming convention to be followed. I.e. 

     public class MyForm extends VerticalLayout {
         // This will match getName/setName in Person
         private TextField name = new TextField(&quot;Name&quot;);
     }

     ...
     MyForm myForm = new MyForm();
     binder.bindInstanceFields(myForm);


Note, that `bindInstanceFields` will bind the fields you did not manually configure with `binder.forField(..)`, not override them.

Second, The `BeanValidationBinder` is a variant of Binder purposed for use with JSR-303 validation annotations in your entities.

    Binder&lt;Person&gt; binder = new BeanValidationBinder&lt;&gt;();

Note, as `bindInstanceFields` wont override existing bindings, if you use `binder.forField(..)` with `BeanValidationBinder` with some `withValidator`, none of the existing JSR-303 annottations on the same property will be used.

If you are not using JSR-303 validation annotations, you should use regular `Binder` instead

    Binder&lt;Person&gt; binder = new Binder&lt;&gt;();

